<node id="&quot;2010&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2010 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period, representing a comprehensive snapshot of life expectancy at birth across numerous countries and regions worldwide. The data reveals significant variation in life expectancy values across different nations during this year.

Among the highest recorded life expectancies in 2010 were Japan (83.08 years), Switzerland (82.20 years), Italy (81.89 years), Australia (81.91 years), and Iceland (81.68 years). Other developed nations also showed high values, including Norway (80.87 years), New Zealand (80.94 years), Sweden (81.30 years), France (81.22 years), and Canada (81.14 years). Regional aggregates included EUR at 75.63 years.

Mid-range life expectancies were recorded across numerous countries, including China (74.65 years), India (67.48 years), the Russian Federation (68.83 years), Pakistan (64.15 years), Brazil (73.35 years), Mexico (71.08 years), and various other nations spanning Latin America, Asia, and Eastern Europe.

Conversely, several countries experienced notably lower life expectancies, including Haiti (39.96 years, noted as a significant anomaly), Eswatini (46.38 years), Lesotho (48.57 years), Somalia (49.52 years), Chad (55.72 years), Mozambique (53.33 years), and various sub-Saharan African nations such as Côte d'Ivoire (57.33 years), Guinea (58.26 years), and Togo (58.64 years). The AFR regional aggregate was recorded at 59.57 years.

The global life expectancy in 2010 was measured at 70.50 years, reflecting the wide disparities in health outcomes and life expectancy across different regions and development levels worldwide.</data>
