<node id="&quot;2009&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2009 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period, representing a comprehensive snapshot of life expectancy at birth across numerous countries and regions worldwide. The year encompasses life expectancy measurements for over 100 countries and regional aggregates, with values ranging from 45.05 years in Eswatini to 83.16 years in Japan, reflecting significant global health disparities.

Notable high life expectancy values in 2009 include Japan (83.16 years), Switzerland (81.89 years), Italy (81.52 years), Australia (81.75 years), Iceland (81.50 years), Sweden (81.15 years), Norway (80.75 years), Canada (80.88 years), and New Zealand (80.56 years). Mid-range developed nations recorded values such as France (81.04 years), Spain (81.33 years), and Denmark (78.88 years).

Conversely, several developing nations recorded notably lower life expectancy values, including Lesotho (47.42 years), Eswatini (45.05 years), Somalia (50.67 years), Chad (55.19 years), and Mozambique (53.33 years). Regional aggregates for 2009 show EUR (Europe) at 75.32 years and AFR (Africa) at 58.84 years.

The data includes specific measurements for countries such as China (74.39 years), India (67.05 years), Russia (68.56 years), Pakistan (63.92 years), Bangladesh (69.60 years), the USA (78.42 years), Brazil (various measurements around 72-73 years), and numerous others across Africa, Asia, Europe, and the Americas. Some entries note a recorded decline in life expectancy for certain regions during this period. 2009 represents the tenth year in several life expectancy tracking sequences, including for Vietnam.</data>
