<node id="&quot;2003&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2003 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period with recorded measurements across numerous countries and regions. Life expectancy values for 2003 vary significantly by geography, reflecting differences in healthcare, development, and living conditions worldwide.

Among the highest recorded life expectancies in 2003 were Japan (82.14 years), Switzerland (80.40 years), Australia (80.57 years), Iceland (80.57 years), Sweden (80.01 years), Norway (79.40 years), Italy (79.81 years), France (79.09 years), and New Zealand (79.06 years). Other developed nations showed strong life expectancy figures, including Canada (79.58 years), Denmark (77.32 years), and the USA (76.99 years).

Mid-range life expectancy values in 2003 included China (71.69 years), India (64.58 years), the Russian Federation (64.72 years), Pakistan (62.15 years), and various other nations ranging from approximately 60 to 76 years.

Lower life expectancy values were recorded in several African and developing nations, including Eswatini (42.59 years), Zimbabwe (45.01 years), Lesotho (45.65 years), Burundi (47.93 years), Somalia (49.50 years), Mozambique (51.67 years), and Côte d'Ivoire (52.20 years).

Regional aggregates for 2003 included AFR (54.27 years) and EUR (72.79 years). The global life expectancy in 2003 was recorded at approximately 67.62 years, representing the average across all measured populations during this year in the data series.</data>
