<node id="&quot;2001&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2001 is a year in global life expectancy data collection with recorded measurements across numerous countries and regions. Life expectancy values for 2001 vary significantly by country, reflecting differences in healthcare, development, and living conditions.

Among countries with the highest recorded life expectancy in 2001 were Japan (81.84 years), Switzerland (80.10 years), Australia (80.13 years), Iceland (79.99 years), Italy (79.68 years), Sweden (79.67 years), Norway (78.75 years), and Israel (78.81 years). Other developed nations showed similarly high values, including France (79.01 years), Denmark (77.04 years), and New Zealand (78.47 years).

Mid-range life expectancy values in 2001 included countries such as China (71.13 years), India (63.66 years), the Russian Federation (65.10 years), Brazil (approximately 71-72 years), and Argentina. Regional aggregates showed EUR at 72.67 years and AFR at 53.47 years.

Countries with lower life expectancy in 2001 included several African nations: Eswatini (44.97 years), Burundi (45.56 years), Zimbabwe (45.43 years), Lesotho (47.97 years), Somalia (49.33 years), Chad (51.59 years), and Côte d'Ivoire (51.50 years). Other nations with notably lower values included Afghanistan, Senegal (59.29 years), and Myanmar (59.78 years).

Global life expectancy in 2001 was recorded at approximately 67.10 years, representing the average across all measured populations during this data collection period.</data>
