<node id="&quot;LIFE EXPECTANCY MEASUREMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">Life Expectancy Measurement is an ongoing annual event spanning from 2000 to 2021 that tracks life expectancy at birth in years across multiple countries and regions. The measurement encompasses diverse geographic areas including developed nations (Australia, Japan, Norway, Luxembourg), emerging economies (Brazil, Vietnam, Indonesia), and developing countries (Uganda, Nigeria, Papua New Guinea, Guinea), as well as regional aggregates like the EUR region.

The data reveals significant variation in life expectancy levels globally. High-income countries such as Japan, Australia, and Norway show life expectancy ranges from approximately 78-84 years, while lower-income nations like Uganda and Niger demonstrate ranges from 48-67 years. Mid-range countries including Costa Rica, Jamaica, and Belize fall between 70-75 years.

Overall trends across the 22-year period show a general upward trajectory in life expectancy for most countries and regions, reflecting improvements in healthcare and living standards. However, notable disruptions appear in 2020-2021, coinciding with the COVID-19 pandemic, where several countries including Brazil, Serbia, Papua New Guinea, and Kyrgyzstan experienced declines. Some countries like Sri Lanka showed anomalous spikes in 2020, while others like Myanmar and Guinea experienced earlier dips in specific years (2008 and 2014 respectively).

The measurement serves as a comprehensive annual health metric documenting population-level life expectancy trends globally over this two-decade period.</data>
