<node id="&quot;LIFE EXPECTANCY AT BIRTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">Life Expectancy at Birth is a health and demographic metric measured in years, representing the average number of years a newborn is expected to live. Tracked annually from 2000 to 2021 across multiple countries and regions globally, this metric serves as a key indicator of population health and longevity trends. The data reveals significant variation by country, with developed nations generally showing higher values (ranging from approximately 77-83 years in countries like Spain, the Netherlands, and Belgium) compared to developing nations (ranging from approximately 40-65 years in countries like Haiti, Sierra Leone, and Zambia). Most countries demonstrated an overall increasing trend over the 2000-2021 period, reflecting improvements in healthcare and living conditions, though many experienced notable declines in 2020-2021, likely attributable to the COVID-19 pandemic. Specific country examples include Spain (79.09-83.14 years), the United Kingdom (77.86-80.10 years), the USA (76.37-78.77 years), Haiti (39.96-63.66 years), and Sierra Leone (49.79-61.02 years), illustrating the wide disparity in life expectancy outcomes across different regions and development levels.</data>
