<node id="&quot;2014&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2014 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period with recorded measurements across numerous countries and regions. Life expectancy values for 2014 vary significantly by country, reflecting differences in healthcare systems, economic development, and living conditions.

Notable high life expectancy values in 2014 include Japan (83.79 years), Switzerland (82.85 years), Italy (82.61 years), Spain (82.58 years), Iceland (82.10 years), Australia (82.37 years), and several other developed nations ranging from 80-82 years. Mid-range values include countries such as China (76.20 years), India (68.92 years), the Russian Federation (70.69 years), and Pakistan (65.39 years). Lower life expectancy values were recorded in countries facing greater health challenges, including Lesotho (48.68 years), Eswatini (50.93 years), Somalia (53.08 years), and South Sudan (59.09 years).

Regional aggregates for 2014 show EUR (Europe) at 76.89 years and AFR (Africa) at 61.97 years. The global life expectancy for 2014 was recorded at 71.95 years. Specific country measurements span the full range from developing nations with life expectancies in the mid-50s to developed nations exceeding 83 years, demonstrating the substantial disparities in life expectancy outcomes across the world during this year.</data>
