<node id="&quot;2021&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2021 represents the final year in a comprehensive global life expectancy data collection period. Across numerous countries and regions, life expectancy values in 2021 varied significantly, ranging from lows of approximately 51-54 years in countries like Lesotho, Somalia, and Eswatini, to highs exceeding 84 years in Japan (84.46 years) and Switzerland (83.33 years). Notable measurements include developed nations such as Norway (82.88 years), Sweden (82.66 years), Australia (83.10 years), and New Zealand (82.20 years) recording high life expectancies, while many African nations recorded lower values. Regional aggregates showed EUR at 76.29 years and AFR at 63.55 years. Several countries experienced declines from 2020, including Myanmar, the Philippines, the USA (76.37 years), and Serbia (72.81 years), while others like Armenia (72.98 years) and Tajikistan (71.81 years) showed recovery. Specific country data included India (67.31 years), China (77.62 years), Canada (81.58 years), and numerous others across all continents. The global life expectancy was recorded at approximately 71.37 years, reflecting continued decline in some regions. 2021 marked the endpoint of the tracked data series for most countries in this dataset.</data>
