<node id="&quot;2016&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2016 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period, representing the seventeenth year in the tracking sequence for multiple countries and regions. During this year, life expectancy measurements were recorded across numerous nations and regional groupings, with values varying significantly based on geographic location and development status.

Life expectancy at birth in 2016 ranged from a low of 49.95 years in Lesotho to a high of 84.15 years in Japan. Notable measurements included Switzerland at 83.17 years, Italy at 82.87 years, Australia at 82.59 years, and Norway at 82.11 years among developed nations. In contrast, countries facing greater health challenges recorded lower values, such as Eswatini at 53.13 years, Somalia at 53.94 years, and South Sudan at 59.19 years.

Regional aggregates for 2016 showed EUR (European region) at 77.35 years and AFR (African region) at 62.92 years. The global average life expectancy was recorded at 72.44 years. Specific country measurements included China at 76.72 years, India at 69.78 years, the USA at 78.56 years, Canada at 81.74 years, Brazil at approximately 75.55 years, and Russia at 71.62 years, among many others across Africa, Asia, Europe, and the Americas. This data reflects the substantial disparities in life expectancy outcomes across different regions and nations during 2016.</data>
