<node id="&quot;2020&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">2020 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period, representing the twenty-first year in the tracking sequence. The year shows varied life expectancy measurements across numerous countries and regions, reflecting diverse health outcomes worldwide.

Life expectancy values in 2020 ranged significantly, from lows of 51.85 years in Lesotho and 55.12925544 years in Somalia to highs of 84.66324868 years in Japan and 83.37 years in Australia. Notable measurements include 82.84 years in Norway, 82.74 years in Switzerland, 82.56117418 years in Iceland, 81.93997914 years in Italy, 81.87409035 years in France, and 81.36821984 years in Denmark. Other developed nations recorded strong figures: 82.37 years in Israel, 82.08200836 years in Sweden, 80.82 years in the measurement period, and 80.6317386 years in recorded data. Canada measured 81.30 years, showing a notable decline from the previous year.

Many countries experienced declines in 2020, likely reflecting the impact of external factors such as the COVID-19 pandemic. The USA recorded 76.89250856 years, showing a significant decline. Other notable declines occurred in Iran (75.19 years), Serbia (74.43296608 years), Spain (81.92498871 years), the Russian Federation (71.38 years), Tajikistan (70.56 years), Pakistan (65.85 years), and various other nations. Global life expectancy was recorded at 72.45 years, showing an overall decline.

Conversely, some regions and countries showed increases or stability. Sri Lanka measured 80.66 years, showing a notable increase. Vietnam recorded 74.77582966 years, marking a notable increase. Malaysia and several other nations demonstrated increases during this period.

Regional aggregates included EUR at 76.92095687 years and AFR at 63.96143556 years. The highest recorded global value was 73.18678447 years. 2020 represents a complex year in global health metrics, characterized by widespread life expectancy fluctuations across different nations and regions.</data>
