<node id="&quot;2006&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1"># Summary of 2006 Life Expectancy Data

2006 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period that encompasses measurements from numerous countries and regions across multiple continents. The data reveals significant variation in life expectancy values across different nations during this year.

Life expectancy measurements in 2006 ranged substantially, from lows of 42.39 years in Lesotho and 42.74 years in Eswatini to highs of 82.59 years in Japan and 81.41 years in Switzerland. Developed nations generally recorded higher life expectancies, including Canada at 80.37 years, Australia at 81.04 years, Iceland at 81.04 years, Italy at 81.06 years, France at 80.53 years, and Norway at 80.28 years. Other notable developed countries recorded values such as New Zealand at 79.89 years, Denmark at 78.19 years, and the USA at 77.68 years.

In Asia, measurements included China at 73.29 years, India at 65.88 years, Sri Lanka at 73.36 years, Thailand at 73.41 years, Myanmar at 62.16 years, and Bangladesh at 68.09 years. African nations showed more varied results, with countries like Zimbabwe at 46.41 years, Somalia at 49.82 years, Mozambique at 52.16 years, Chad at 53.09 years, and Burundi at 54.95 years recording lower values, while others such as Tunisia at 75.58 years and Libya at 74.61 years recorded higher values.

Regional aggregates were also recorded, including EUR (Europe) at 74.11 years and AFR (Africa) at 56.44 years. The global life expectancy measurement for 2006 was recorded at 68.98 years, reflecting the worldwide average across all nations tracked in this comprehensive data collection period.</data>
