<node id="&quot;2007&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1"># Comprehensive Summary: 2007

2007 is a year in the global life expectancy data collection period, representing the eighth year in multiple life expectancy tracking sequences. During this year, life expectancy measurements were recorded across numerous countries and regions worldwide, with significant variation reflecting differences in healthcare infrastructure, economic development, and public health conditions.

Life expectancy values in 2007 ranged considerably across the globe. Developed nations generally recorded higher values, including Switzerland at 81.60 years, Japan at 82.76 years, Italy at 81.17 years, Iceland at 81.15 years, and Australia at 81.37 years. European nations such as France (80.80 years), Sweden (80.77 years), Norway (80.35 years), and Denmark (78.29 years) also demonstrated high life expectancy. Other developed regions including Canada (80.38 years), New Zealand (80.04 years), and Israel (80.12 years) similarly recorded elevated values.

Mid-range life expectancy values in 2007 included countries such as China (73.84 years), the Russian Federation (67.42 years), India (66.09 years), and various Latin American nations including Argentina, Cuba, and Brazil. Regional aggregates showed EUR at 74.52 years and AFR at 57.29 years.

Lower life expectancy values were recorded in several developing nations, particularly in sub-Saharan Africa. Notable examples include Eswatini (43.60 years), Lesotho (43.89 years), Zimbabwe (47.34 years), Somalia (49.97 years), Mozambique (52.59 years), Chad (53.97 years), and Burundi (56.45 years). Other countries with lower recorded values included Côte d'Ivoire (55.73 years), the Democratic Republic of the Congo (55.97 years), and Senegal (63.89 years).

The global life expectancy in 2007 was recorded at approximately 69.42 years, reflecting the weighted average across all nations and regions included in the data collection period.</data>
